{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"HTML Drag and Drop","slug":"html-drag-and-drop","subject":"HTML","category":"Web Development","level":"Intermediate","estimated_read_time":"20 minutes","prerequisites":["HTML Attributes"],"learning_objectives":["Make elements draggable","Handle drag events (dragstart, dragover, drop)","Transfer data during drag"],"theory":"# HTML Drag and Drop API\n\nHTML5 standardizes Drag and Drop functionality. Any element can be made draggable.\n\n## The Drag Process\n\n1.  **Make Draggable:** Set `draggable=\"true\"` on the element.\n2.  **Drag Start:** Define what happens when dragging starts (store data).\n3.  **Drag Over:** Allow the drop by preventing default behavior.\n4.  **Drop:** Define what happens when dropped (read data).\n\n## Example Workflow\n\n### 1. The Item\n```html\n<img id=\"drag1\" src=\"img.png\" draggable=\"true\" ondragstart=\"drag(event)\">\n```\n\n### 2. The JavaScript\n```javascript\nfunction drag(ev) {\n  ev.dataTransfer.setData(\"text\", ev.target.id);\n}\n\nfunction allowDrop(ev) {\n  ev.preventDefault(); // Must do this to allow dropping\n}\n\nfunction drop(ev) {\n  ev.preventDefault();\n  var data = ev.dataTransfer.getData(\"text\");\n  ev.target.appendChild(document.getElementById(data));\n}\n```\n\n### 3. The Drop Zone\n```html\n<div ondrop=\"drop(event)\" ondragover=\"allowDrop(event)\"></div>\n```","syntax":"<div draggable=\"true\" ondragstart=\"...\">","examples":[{"code":"<!-- See theory code for full implementation -->","output":"Moves an element from one div to another.","explanation":"The appendChild() method moves the DOM node, effectively 'dropping' it."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Forgetting event.preventDefault()","correction":"By default, elements generally cannot be dropped into other elements. You MUST call preventDefault() in the ondragover event handler.","example":"Without it, the drop event never fires."}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"How do you make an element draggable?","difficulty":"Easy","answer":"Set the draggable=\"true\" attribute."},{"question":"What is dataTransfer?","difficulty":"Advanced","answer":"It is an object used to hold the data that is being dragged during a drag and drop operation. methods like setData() and getData() are used to handle the payload."}],"practice_problems":[{"difficulty":"Advanced","problem":"Create a simple code structure to drag a <p> element into a <div>.","hint":"Needs draggable=true, ondragstart, ondragover, ondrop.","solution":"(Complex JS required, see theory)"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Trello/Kanban Boards","description":"Task management apps rely heavily on the Drag and Drop API to move cards between columns.","code":"ev.dataTransfer..."}],"exam_notes":["draggable=\"true\"","Events: ondragstart, ondragover, ondrop","ondragover must preventDefault()","dataTransfer object handles the info"],"summary":"The Drag and Drop API brings desktop-like interaction to the web. By handling specific events and using the dataTransfer object, you can create intuitive interfaces where users organize content by moving elements visually.","order":12},"courseTutorials":[{"slug":"html-document-structure","path":"content/html/html-document-structure.json","title":"HTML Document Structure","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":2},{"slug":"html-comments","path":"content/html/html-comments.json","title":"HTML Comments","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":3},{"slug":"html-editors","path":"content/html/html-editors.json","title":"HTML Editors & Tools","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":4},{"slug":"html-elements","path":"content/html/html-elements.json","title":"HTML Elements","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":5},{"slug":"html-attributes","path":"content/html/html-attributes.json","title":"HTML Attributes","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order